05057nam a22009615i 9783110376081DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20142014gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2019403307  a(OCoLC)898770092  a97831103760817 a10.1515/97831103760812doi  a(DE-B1597)429567  a(OCoLC)893939908  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aBS2655.L3bC66 2014 4aBS2651b.C669 2014 7aREL0067202bisacsh04a227.06223  aBC 72702rvk0(DE-625)rvk/9628:1 aConway, Kevin P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Promises of God :bThe Background of Paul’s Exclusive Use of 'epangelia' for the Divine Pledge /cKevin P. Conway. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (297 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBeihefte zur Zeitschrift für die neutestamentliche Wissenschaft ,x0171-6441 ;v2110 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis study is the first to investigate why Paul makes exclusive use of 'epangelia' for the divine pledge when referring to the Abrahamic covenant, a usage of the term never found in the OT-LXX. After examining Jewish writings and Greek literature of the classical and Hellenistic periods, this study demonstrates that Paul is rather unique in his exclusive use of the 'epangelia' word group for the divine pledge and for using the term predominantly in reference to the Abrahamic promises. This exclusive usage is further deemed unexpected in that the 'horkos' and 'omnymi' lexemes are by far the terms most commonly associated with God's promises to Abraham in the OT, the literature with which Paul was most familiar. The study then moves to explain why Paul has chosen this path of discontinuity, where it is argued that Paul's exclusive choice of 'epangelia' for the divine promise is driven by its conceptual and linguistic correspondence with the 'euangelion', one of the terms Paul adopted from the early church that forms the core of his ministry. This conceptual word study of the divine promise will benefit Pauline scholars interested in Paul's use of the OT as well as his association of the 'euangelion' and 'epangelia' word groups.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aEpangelia (The Greek word) 0aEpangelia (The Greek word). 0aGod (Christianity)xPromisesxBiblical teaching. 0aGodxPromises. 4aAbraham. 4aEvangelien. 4aHellenistisches Judentum. 4aPaulus. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Studies / Paul's Letters.2bisacsh  aAbraham.  aGospel.  aHellenistic Judaism.  aPaul (Apostle).  apromise.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Theology and Religious Studies 2000-2014 (EN)z978311023854908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Theology and Religious Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110638165oZDB-23-GTR08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theology, Religion, Judaism 2014z9783110370409oZDB-23-DGF0 cEPUBz97831104102730 cprintz978311037507740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311037608140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110376081423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110376081/original  a978-3-11-023854-9  DGBA Backlist Theology and Religious Studies 2000-2014 (EN)c2000d2014  a978-3-11-023857-0  DGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1c2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSH